<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-09-02T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-09-02T18:00:00-05:00" n="735" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d735">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77/1670: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Chargé in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Wright</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-09-02T19:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">September
                                            2, 1920—7 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                            <p>947. Your 1256, August 18, 9 p.m. Referring to point 2, part C. It
                                was proposed that the notes of the Chinese Eastern Railway might be
                                guaranteed by the Chinese Government, as without such guarantee
                                bankers would not consider them marketable securities. Russian
                                interests object to this plan as they fear that sometime in the
                                future such a guarantee might be used by the Chinese Government to
                                enforce claims to the railway property.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Colby</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>